    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-07-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-07-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="441"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d441">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.51 War Credits/673</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 104</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-07-13">July 13,
                            1934</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I enclose a copy of a memorandum<note n="9"
                        xml:id="d441fn9">Not printed.</note> regarding the payment to this
                    Government on July 6, 1934 of $196,128 by the Government of <pb facs="0642"
                        n="542" xml:id="pg_542"/> Greece. As explained in this memorandum the sum in
                    question is understood to represent 27½ per cent of the interest payments due
                    May 10 and November 10, 1933, and 35 per cent of the interest payment due on May
                    10, 1934, on the “new loan” provided for in Part II of the American-Hellenic
                    Debt Funding Agreement of May 10, 1929.</p>
                <p>The Department would be interested in receiving your comments on this payment,
                    particularly any information as to whether the necessary funds were released by
                    the International Financial Commission and, if so, whether the release met with
                    the approval of the French member of the Commission.</p>
                <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
